'''''Zhongfeng Mingben''''' ({{zh|中峰明本|w=Chung-feng Ming-pen}} {{nihongo|Chūhō Myōhon}}, 1263–1323){{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=155}} was a [[Chan Buddhism|Chan Buddhist]] master who lived at the beginning of [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan China]]. He adhered to the rigorous style of the [[Linji school]] and influenced [[Zen]] through several Japanese teachers who studied under him.{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b}}

==Biography==
Zhongfeng Mingben's family name was Sun.{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=50}} He was the youngest of seven children.{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=50}} His mother died when he was nine years old.{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=51}} Already in his teenage years he wanted to become a monk.{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=51}} From fifteen he observed the [[Upāsaka and Upāsikā|layman]]'s [[Five Precepts]].{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=51}} His left hand became mutilated when, in his youth he burned the little finger as a sacrifice to the Buddha.{{sfn|Patry Leidy|2009|p=352}} This may have been inspired by chapter 23 of the ''[[Lotus Sutra]]'':{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=51}}
{{quote|If there is one, opening up his thought, wishes to attain [[Enlightenment in Buddhism|Anuttarā samyaksaṃbodhi]], if he can burn a finger or a toe as an offering to a Buddhastupa, he shall exceed one who uses realm or walled city, wife or children, or even all the lands, mountains, forests, rivers, ponds, and sundry precious objects in the whole thousand-million-fold world as offerings.{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=51}}}}

In 1287 Zhongfeng Mingben received [[tonsure]] at Shiziyuan [[vihara|Monastery]] on [[Tianmu Mountain]].{{sfn|Patry Leidy|2009|p=352}} In 1288 he was ordained as a [[bhikkhu|monk]].{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=52}} Contrary to the norm, he grew long hair in (presumed) accordance with his teacher, Gaofeng Yuanmai.{{sfn|Patry Leidy|2009|p=352}}

As a young man he was appointed to succeed the abbot of the monastery on Tianmu Mountain, but fled the monastery in a search for solitude.{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=159}}

As an adult he had an "overpowering physical build".{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=159}} He was called "The old Buddha south of the sea", an allusion to [[Mazu Daoyi]], (709–788){{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=159}} one of the most influential teachers of Chan Buddhism, who lived during the [[Tang dynasty]] (618–907), the "golden age of Zen".{{sfn|McRae|2003}} Zhongfeng Mingben declined a number of titles, appointments and positions, temporarily choosing instead a life of wandering and solitary meditation.{{sfn|Patry Leidy|2009|p=352}} He turned down an invitation of [[Ayurbarwada Buyantu Khan]] to come to the [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan court]].{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=197}}

==Teachings==

===Illusion===
In Zhongfeng Mingben's ''Huanzhu Jiaxun'', "Family instructions of Illusory Abiding",{{sfn|Heller|2009a}} he describes himself as "the illusionary man", alluding to the play of [[Maya (illusion)|Maya]] and the ability of tricksters to create an illusionary world.{{sfn|Heller|2009a|pp=271–277}} Zhongfeng Mingben states that this world is illusory, but that there is no alternative to this illusion. Students have to realize the pervasiveness of this illusion, and learn to act within it.{{sfn|Heller|2009a|p=273}} The alternative for this illusionary or relative world, [[Two truths doctrine|the absolute truth]], is not to be regarded as an enduring phenomenon.{{sfn|Heller|2009a|p=294}}

Zhongfeng Mingben relies on the ''[[Sutra of Perfect Enlightenment]]'' in his teachings on how to overcome this illusion.{{sfn|Heller|2009a|p=285}} This sutra gives metaphors connected to illusion to explain the insubstantial nature of ignorance, such as dreams or flowers in the sky.{{sfn|Heller|2009a|p=285}}{{refn|group=note|"Flowers in the sky" is translated in Japanese as "Kuge" (ch. 19; "[[Shobogenzo]]" by [[Dogen Zenji]]). Sky stands for "empty" thus "Flowers in the empty". This corresponds to the principle of the [[Impermanence|insubstantiality]] (one of the [[Three marks of existence|three seals of Buddhism]]) thus that everything exists and nothing is real, in the sense that nothing has its own fixed reality, fixed measure, fixed form, nothing that is alive, has its own nature or independent, autonomous substantiality.<ref group=web>[http://www.flowersinthesky.com/fnc_en.htm Cultural association "Flowers in the Sky"]</ref>}}{{refn|group=note|The Sutra of Perfect Enlightenment says: "What is ignorance? Good sons, all sentient beings fall into various inverted views without beginning. Just like a disoriented person who confuses the four directions, they mistakenly take the [[Mahābhūta|Four Elements]] as the attributes of their bodies and the conditioned shadows of the [[Ṣaḍāyatana|Six Objects]] as the attributes of their mind. It is just like when our eyes are diseased and we see flowers in the sky, or a second moon. Good sons, the sky actually has no flowers—they are the false attachment of the diseased person. And because of this false attachment, not only are we confused about the self-nature of the sky; we are also mixed up about the place where real flowers come from. From this, there is the falsely existent transmigration through life and death. Therefore it is called "ignorance."<ref group=web>[http://www.acmuller.net/bud-canon/sutra_of_perfect_enlightenment.html The Sutra of Perfect Enlightenment (Yuanjue jing), translated by Charles Muller] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015054918/http://www.acmuller.net/bud-canon/sutra_of_perfect_enlightenment.html |date=October 15, 2014 }}</ref>}} Illusory phenomena emerge from an intrinsically pure ground.{{refn|group=note|The [[Buddha nature]], or the [[Eight Consciousnesses#Aālayavijñāna|Aālayavijñāna]]}} Since the illusions are not real in themselves, their disappearance will not change this pure ground. But the disappearance itself is also illusionary since the mind is enlightened or pure from the beginning. This makes it impossible to speak of either being enlightened or unenlightened, a position which is clearly at odds with basic Buddhist teachings. This is "cured" by overcoming "the discriminating thought processes that posit terms like ''illusion'' and ''real''".{{sfn|Heller|2009a|pp=287–288}}

===Physical practice===
Illusion is also created by relying on words. There are alternative, non-discursive ways of relating to words, one of them being ''k'an-hua'', "observing the key phrase", the method of [[Kōan#Observing the phrase|kōan study]] introduced by [[Dahui Zonggao]] (1089–1163).{{sfn|Heller|2009a|pp=273 & 303}} Insight must be based in bodily experience rather than mere intellectual discrimination.

Another physical practice is calligraphy, the writing of characters. This writing is a bodily act. The writing of a character is not an intellectual inquiry, but "a performance of it".{{sfn|Heller|2009a|p=302}} Zhongfeng Mingben was a celebrated calligraphy artist.{{sfn|Lauer|2002}}

===Pure Land===
Zhongfeng Mingben merged Chán with [[Pure Land Buddhism|Pure Land]] teachings.{{sfn|Payne|Tanaka|2004|p=212}} Together with [[Yongming Yanshou]]  (904–975), who lived three centuries earlier, he was an influential proponent of this dual practice.{{sfn|Payne|Tanaka|2004|p=212}}

==Influence==

===Monastic discipline===
Zhongfeng Mingben lived after the "golden age of Chán" of the Tang and the proliferation of Chán during the Tang. His age was regarded as an age of ''mofa'' ([[Mappō|"Degenerate age of the Law"]]).{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=50}} Zhongfeng Mingben attributed this to a lack of monastic discipline and a lack of personal dedication by monks,{{sfn|Lauer|2002|p=50}} and tried to counter this by writing a monastic code, the ''Huan-chu ch'ing-kuei'' (Jpn. ''Genju shingi''), in 1317.{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=161}} This work influenced [[Musō Soseki]], a contemporary of Zhongfeng Mingben, when he wrote his guidelines for monasteries and monks, the ''Rinsen kakun''.{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=161}}

===Gong-an===
{{further|Kōan}}
Zhongfeng Mingben was the first to compare the sayings and teachings of the 'masters of the old' with the public cases of the court, the ''gong-an''.

According to Zhongfeng Mingben ''gōng'àn'' abbreviates ''gōngfǔ zhī àndú'' (公府之案牘, Japanese ''kōfu no antoku'' – literally the ''andu'' "official correspondence; documents; files" of a ''gongfu''  "government post"), which referred to a "public record" or the "case records of a public law court" in [[Tang dynasty|Tang-dynasty]] China.{{sfn|Sasaki|1965|pp=4–6}}{{sfn|Foulk|2000|pp=21–22}}{{refn|group=note|Assertions that the literal meaning of ''kung-an'' is the table, desk, or bench of a magistrate appear on page 18 of Foulk 2000. See also {{sfn|McRae|2003|pp=172–173, note 16}}}} ''Kōan/gong'an'' thus serves as a [[metaphor]] for principles of reality beyond the private opinion of one person, and a teacher may test the student's ability to recognize and understand that principle.

===Japanese Zen===
[[File:Epistle to Zhongfeng Mingben.jpg|right|thumb|240px|Epistle to Zhongfeng Mingben {{nobreak|(与中峰明本尺牘, yochūhō myōhon sekitoku)}} One of six letters, ink on paper; {{nobreak|[[Seikadō Bunko Art Museum]]}}, Tokyo]]

Several Japanese Buddhists came to China to study with Zhongfeng Mingben on Mount T'ien-mu. They formed the Genjū line of the [[Five Mountain System#The Rinka|Rinka monasteries]], the more independent monasteries outside the cities and the [[Five Mountain System]] of government-approved temples. Kosen Ingen   was the most important of these Japanese students.{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=197}}{{refn|group=note| (1295–1374) Founding priest of [[Chōju-ji (Kamakura)|Hōkizan Chōju-ji]] temple, [[Kenchoji|Kenchoji School]], Rinzai<ref group=web>{{cite web|title=Chojuji |url=http://www.asahi-net.or.jp/~qm9t-kndu/chojuji.htm |accessdate=18 October 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805175751/http://www.asahi-net.or.jp/~QM9T-KNDU/chojuji.htm |archivedate=August 5, 2012 }}</ref>}} Other students include Kohō Kakumyō, a teacher of [[Bassui Tokushō]],{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=199}} and [[Jakushitsu Genkō]] (1290–1367), the founder of [[Eigen-ji]].{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|pp=203–204}}

Although they never met, Zhongfeng Mingben had a close affinity with [[Musō Soseki]], via the Japanese students who studied with him.{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005b|p=159}}

===Wild fox slobber===
[[Hakuin|Hakuin's]] warning against "wild fox slobber" can be traced back to Zhongfeng Mingben.{{sfn|Hakuin|2009|pp=243–244, note 15}} The term "wild fox" points to teachers who lead students astray by giving wrong information. The term wild fox is also the name of the [[Wild fox koan]]. Whereas Zhongfeng Mingben warns against the impossible attempt of totally silencing the mind,{{sfn|Hakuin|2009|pp=243–244, note 15}} Hakuin uses the term in a more positive sense, to denote the workings of koans, which "possess the power to cause sudden death in students, raising the great doubt in their minds that will lead them to the 'great death' and the rebirth of [[satori]] and [[Enlightenment in Buddhism|enlightenment]]".{{sfn|Hakuin|2009|pp=243–244, note 15}}

==Criticism==
Zhongfeng Mingben's teachings mark the beginning of a development in Chinese Chán which made it vulnerable in the competition with other teachings:
{{quote|[T]he tradition came to be increasingly anti-intellectual in orientation and, in the process, reduced its complex heritage to simple formulae for which literal interpretations were thought to be adequate.{{sfn|Wright|2000|pp=209–210}}}}

This development left Chinese Chán vulnerable for criticisms by neo-Confucianism, which developed after the [[Song dynasty]]. Its anti-intellectual rhetoric was no match for the intellectual discourse of the neo-Confucianists.{{sfn|Wright|2000|pp=210–211}}

